    "content": "<html lang=\"en\">\n<head>\n<meta charset=\"UTF-8\" />\n<meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1\" />\n<title>P vs NP Demonstration</title>\n<style>\n  body {\n    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\n    margin: 2rem;\n    background: #f9f9f9;\n    color: #222;\n  }\n  h1, h2 {\n    color: #2c3e50;\n  }\n  p {\n    max-width: 700px;\n    line-height: 1.5;\n  }\n  .container {\n    margin-top: 1.5rem;\n  }\n  .section {\n    background: white;\n    padding: 1rem 2rem 2rem 2rem;\n    margin-bottom: 2rem;\n    border-radius: 6px;\n    box-shadow: 0 2px 6px #ccc;\n  }\n  label {\n    font-weight: bold;\n  }\n  input[type=number] {\n    width: 3.5rem;\n    padding: 0.25rem 0.5rem;\n    margin-left: 0.5rem;\n    font-size: 1rem;\n  }\n  button {\n    margin-top: 0.8rem;\n    padding: 0.5rem 1.2rem;\n    font-size: 1rem;\n    background-color: #2980b9;\n    border: none;\n    color: white;\n    border-radius: 4px;\n    cursor: pointer;\n  }\n  button:disabled {\n    background-color: #95a5a6;\n    cursor: default;\n  }\n  pre {\n    background: #ecf0f1;\n    padding: 1rem;\n    overflow-x: auto;\n    border-radius: 6px;\n  }\n  .time {\n    font-weight: bold;\n  }\n  .result {\n    margin-top: 1rem;\n    white-space: pre-wrap;\n  }\n  footer {\n    margin-top: 3rem;\n    font-size: 0.9rem;\n    color: #666;\n    border-top: 1px solid #ddd;\n    padding-top: 1rem;\n    max-width: 700px;\n  }\n  a {\n    color: #2980b9;\n  }\n</style>\n</head>\n<body>\n  <h1>Understanding <em>P vs NP</em> with a Simple Example</h1>\n  <p><strong>P vs NP</strong> is one of the most important open problems in theoretical computer science. Informally:</p>\n  <ul>\n    <li><strong>P</strong> is the class of problems which can be <em>solved quickly</em> (in polynomial time) by a computer.</li>\n    <li><strong>NP</strong> is the class of problems where a given solution can be <em>verified quickly</em>.</li>\n  </ul>\n  <p>The famous question: <strong>Is P equal to NP?</strong> In other words: can every problem whose solution can be quickly verified also be quickly solved?</p>\n\n  <div class=\"container\">\n    <div class=\"section\" id=\"demo-section\">\n      <h2>Demo: Subset Sum Problem (NP) vs Brute Force Search (P?!)</h2>\n      <p>\n        The <strong>Subset Sum Problem</strong> asks: Given a list of numbers and a target sum, is there a subset of numbers that add up exactly to the target?\n      </p>\n      <p>\n        Verifying a candidate subset sums to the target is easy and fast (P). Finding such a subset quickly is believed to not be efficiently possible (NP-Complete). Here we demonstrate a brute force search that checks all subsets - which grows exponentially.\n      </p>\n      <label for=\"numItems\">Number of items (max 20):</label>\n      <input type=\"number\" id=\"numItems\" min=\"1\" max=\"20\" value=\"15\" />\n      <button id=\"runBtn\">Run Subset Sum Search</button>\n      <div class=\"result\" id=\"result\"></div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <footer>\n    <p>\n      <strong>Note:</strong> This is a simplified demonstration of P vs NP concepts for educational purposes. The Subset Sum problem is NP-Complete, no known polynomial time algorithm exists.\n    </p>\n    <p>Learn more: <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P_versus_NP_problem\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Wikipedia: P versus NP problem</a></p>\n  </footer>\n\n<script>\n(() => {\n  const runBtn = document.getElementById('runBtn');\n  const numItemsInput = document.getElementById('numItems');\n  const resultDiv = document.getElementById('result');\n\n  // Generate a random integer array between 1 and 100\n  function generateNumbers(n) {\n    const arr = [];\n    for(let i = 0; i < n; i++) {\n      arr.push(Math.floor(Math.random() * 100) + 1);\n    }\n    return arr;\n  }\n\n  // Brute force check for subset sum:\n  // Checks all subsets by bitmask enumeration\n  // Returns one subset that sums exactly to target or null if none found\n  function subsetSumBruteForce(numbers, target) {\n    const n = numbers.length;\n    const totalSubsets = 1 << n; // 2^n\n    for(let mask = 0; mask < totalSubsets; mask++) {\n      let sum = 0;\n      let subset = [];\n      for(let i = 0; i < n; i++) {\n        if(mask & (1 << i)) {\n          sum += numbers[i];\n          subset.push(numbers[i]);\n        }\n      }\n      if(sum === target) {\n        return subset;\n      }\n    }\n    return null;\n  }\n\n  // Given numbers, choose a random target as sum of random subset\n  function generateTarget(numbers) {\n    let targetSubset = [];\n    for(let i = 0; i < numbers.length; i++) {\n      if(Math.random() < 0.5) targetSubset.push(numbers[i]);\n    }\n    if(targetSubset.length === 0) {\n      targetSubset.push(numbers[0]);\n    }\n    const target = targetSubset.reduce((a,b) => a + b, 0);\n    return {target, targetSubset};\n  }\n\n  // Handler for running the demo\n  runBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {\n    const n = parseInt(numItemsInput.value, 10);\n    if(isNaN(n) || n < 1 || n > 20) {\n      alert(\"Please enter a valid number of items between 1 and 20.\");\n      return;\n    }\n\n    runBtn.disabled = true;\n    resultDiv.textContent = \"Generating numbers and target...\";\n\n    // Generate numbers and target subset sum\n    const numbers = generateNumbers(n);\n    const {target, targetSubset} = generateTarget(numbers);\n\n    resultDiv.innerHTML =\n      `<p><strong>Numbers:</strong> [${numbers.join(', ')}]</p>` +\n      `<p><strong>Target sum:</strong> ${target}</p>` +\n      `<p><em>Running brute force subset sum search (may take a few seconds)...</em></p>`;\n\n    // Run subset sum brute force and measure time\n    setTimeout(() => {\n      const startTime = performance.now();\n      const foundSubset = subsetSumBruteForce(numbers, target);\n      const endTime = performance.now();\n      const timeSec = ((endTime - startTime) / 1000).toFixed(3);\n\n      let output = `<p class=\"time\">Time taken: ${timeSec} seconds</p>`;\n      if(foundSubset) {\n        output += `<p><strong>Subset found summing to target:</strong> [${foundSubset.join(', ')}]</p>`;\n        if(arraysEqualUnordered(foundSubset, targetSubset)) {\n          output += `<p><em>The found subset matches the generated target subset!</em></p>`;\n        } else {\n          output += `<p><em>The found subset is a valid alternative solution.</em></p>`;\n        }\n      } else {\n        output += `<p><strong>No subset found that sums to the target.</strong></p>`;\n      }\n\n      output += `<hr /><p>\n<strong>Interpretation:</strong> This brute force algorithm checks all subsets, which takes time proportional to 2^n (exponential).<br/>\nAs n grows, it quickly becomes impractical.<br/>\nThis illustrates why <em>solving</em> such NP problems quickly (<em>P</em>) is hard, even though <em>verifying</em> a proposed solution is easy.\n</p>`;\n\n      resultDiv.innerHTML += output;\n      runBtn.disabled = false;\n    }, 100);\n  });\n\n  // Helper to compare two arrays if they contain the same elements regardless of order\n  function arraysEqualUnordered(a, b) {\n    if(a.length !== b.length) return false;\n    const countMap = new Map();\n    for(const x of a) {\n      countMap.set(x, (countMap.get(x) ?? 0) + 1);\n    }\n    for(const y of b) {\n      if(!countMap.has(y)) return false;\n      const c = countMap.get(y);\n      if(c === 1) countMap.delete(y);\n      else countMap.set(y, c - 1);\n    }\n    return countMap.size === 0;\n  }\n})();\n</script>\n</body>\n</html>"
